About the project

During the course we will learn how to use open data and open research tools tool. We will understand the principles, advantages and possibilities for using these open research tools (Rstudio, Github, RMarkDown). Following methods will be used during the course: Regression models, Clustering and classification, Discriminant analysis (DA), K-means clustering (KMC), Dimensionality reduction techniques, Principal component analysis (PCA), Multiple Correspondence analysis (MCA)

Exercise 2

Background

The dataset students2014 contains information from 166 students attending an introductory course at the University of Helsinki. Students answered questions regarding learning approaches. The data contains 7 variables: age, gender, attitude (the global attitude attitude toward statistics), deep (higher points indicate a strong need to engage in the actual content), stra (higher points indicate strategies used that maximices the the chance to get a high grade) , surf (higher points indicate an intention to get trough with least amonut of trouble) and points (Exam points).

Distributions

Figure 1 shows the density distributions of each variable. All variables except age looks more or less normally distributed. Age is skewed.Similar distributions is noted among men and women.

Relationships

Figure 1 also shows correlation coffiecient for the each relationship between variables and scatteplots illustrating the relationship. The strongest correlation is between attitude and points, the variables are moderately positively correlated (Cor=0.437) and similar among women and men (Figure 1 and 2). A moderate negative correlations is observed between deep and surface questions (cor -0.324), which is considerably higher among men (Men: -0.622 vs women:-0.087, Figure 1 and 3). For all other relationships, the correlation is low (<0.30).

Linear regression

We run a linear regression to test how much attitude, age and gender explain the exam points. Of the included variables, there was only a statistically significant relationship between attitude and exam points (P=8.34e-09). Each increase 1 score increase in attitude increased the exam points by 3.6 points. Age and gender was removed from analysis, since they were did statistically significantly associate with exam points and the analysis was rerun.The attitude explained 18.56 % of the variability in Exam points.

my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude+age+gender, data = students2014)

summary(my_model)

Draw diagnostic plots

The Residual vs fitted plot is used to detect non-linearity, unequal error variances, and outliers, which linear regression assume there is not. Based on the plot it looks like there are some outliers.

The residuals ar located quite randomly around the 0 line, which suggest that the assumption that the relationship is linear correct.

three of residual stands out from the pattern of residuals, suggesting there are some outliers.

In the residuals vs leverege plot you can se that the outlier observations have a value of x that is far from the average of x.

Background (Brief description of data)

The data is collected during the 2005-2006 school year from two public schools (secondary education) in Portugal. The data include student grades, demographic, social and school related variables, which were collected by using school reports and questionnaires.Among these is also alcohol use. Two datasets are provided regarding the performance in two distinct subjects: Mathematics (mat) and Portuguese language (por). These two have been combined into one file.

Variables G1, G2, G3 are the grades from period 1 to 3 (3 is final grade). Range is from 0-20 and an description of the range of points is in table 1.

Step 3-4

Personal hypotheses

I chose the following interesting variables from the datset: sex, adress" (students home address type, rural or urban), famrel (from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent) and higher (wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)). My personal hypotheses regarding these variables and their effect on alcohol consuption is:

Students of male sex, with poor family relationships,that dont want to make a higher eduction and live in an urban environment drink more alcohol.

Numerical and graphical exploration of the variables

Based on a numerical exploration of the data, it seems that familial relationships are slightly better among non-high alcohol users (table 2a), as hypothesized. However, the mean alcohol intake seem to be higher among persons living in an rural envoronment(2b), which was unexpected. Those that wanted to take an higher eductation and persons of male sex had on average a higher alcohol intake (Table 2c-d). The same is also clear from the distribution figures of the selected variables (figure1a-d)

step 5

Logistic regression

Present and interpret a summary of the fitted model. Based on the summary of the fitted model, familial relationships are negatively associated with high alcohol use (P=0.02), having an urban address is negatively associatiod with alcohol but not on a statistically significant level (P=0.08), male sex is positively associated with high alcohol use (P=0.0002) and wanting to take a higher education is negatively associated (but not statistically significant!) with high alcohol use. The z- and p-values are based on the wald test, which is used in the model to test whether the pairwise difference between the coefficient and the reference class and the other class is different from zero or not (categorical values). Table 3 contains the Odds ratios of the modelled variables (and 95%CI), which were calculated by taking the exponent of the coefficients. By looking at these, we can say that for each increase(=improvement)in familial relationships there was 27% decrease in high use of alcohol, with the true population effect between 43% and 6%. persons having an urban address were 28% less likely to be high users of alcohol, howeve this observation was not statistically significant.

glm_res <- glm(high_use ~ famrel + address +sex+higher, data = alc, family = "binomial")
